                      </div>
                      <figcaption class="dcr-o6npt4">
                        <span class="dcr-17eagbs"
                          ><svg width="18" height="13" viewBox="0 0 18 13">
                            <path
                              d="M18 3.5v8l-1.5 1.5h-15l-1.5-1.5v-8l1.5-1.5h3.5l2-2h4l2 2h3.5l1.5 1.5zm-9 7.5c1.9 0 3.5-1.6 3.5-3.5s-1.6-3.5-3.5-3.5-3.5 1.6-3.5 3.5 1.6 3.5 3.5 3.5z"
                            /></svg></span
                        ><span class="dcr-1y4fm6e"
                          >Colorful seaside village of Brixham Devon<br />The
                          coastal village of Brixham, Devon.</span
                        >
                        Photograph: Geoff Eccles/Getty Images/iStockphoto
                      </figcaption>
                    </figure>

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      Combine walks through lush open fields, over rugged
                      headlands and shady woodland with time dipping into
                      Dartmouth’s art galleries and boutiques, and tucking into
                      fresh fish suppers in Brixham, a colourful small port set
                      around a picturesque harbour. The first stretch begins
                      relatively gently, along the long shingle beach at Slapton
                      Sands, before becoming increasingly rugged as the cliffs
                      rise up to form dramatic headlands.
                    </p>

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      Dartmouth makes an ideal base if you want to mix walking
                      with more urban pleasures. Check into Browns, a stylish
                      boutique hotel with a buzzy brasserie (doubles from £160,
                      B&amp;B,
                      <a
                        href="https://www.brownshoteldartmouth.co.uk/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >brownshoteldartmouth.co.uk</a
                      >), or round up family or friends and stay at the Spinners
                      House (sleeps eight, from £838 per week,
                      <a
                        href="https://www.sykescottages.co.uk/cottage/Devon-Dartmouth/Spinners-House-1118115.html"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >sykescottages.co.uk</a
                      >).
                    </p>

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      The stretch from Dartmouth to Brixham is one of the
                      trail’s most challenging, but there are plenty of rewards:
                      the 15th-century castle at
                      <a
                        href="https://www.kingswearcastle.org/history/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >Kingswear</a
                      >, the limestone meadows around
                      <a
                        href="https://www.countryside-trust.org.uk/explore/berry-head/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >Berry Head</a
                      >
                      that blaze with wildflowers from May to August, and the
                      linnets, skylarks and rare
                      <a
                        href="https://www.rspb.org.uk/birds-and-wildlife/wildlife-guides/bird-a-z/cirl-bunting/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >cirl buntings</a
                      >, swooping in the skies above
                      <a
                        href="https://www.nci-frowardpoint.org.uk/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >Froward Point</a
                      >.
                    </p>

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      Brixham itself is a fantastic place in which to end a
                      walk, with excellent fish restaurants dotted through the
                      town; arguably the best is Rockfish (<a
                        href="https://therockfish.co.uk/"
                        data-link-name="in body link"
                        >therockfish.co.uk</a
                      >), situated in the famous fish market, overlooking the
                      boats as they land their catch.
                    </p>

                    </div>

                    <!-- End of walks -->

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      <span data-dcr-style="bullet"></span> This article was
                      amended on 9 August 2023 because an earlier version
                      suggested that the Heanton Court pub was located in
                      Braunton on the route for Walk 4 and would serve as a
                      lunch spot. In fact it is a few miles past Braunton.
                    </p>

                    <p class="dcr-1kas69x">
                      <em class="dcr-1kas69x"
                        >For more information, downloadable maps and route
                        planners, visit
                        <a
                          href="https://www.southwestcoastpath.org.uk/"
                          data-link-name="in body link"
                          >southwestcoastpath.org.uk</a
                        ></em
                      >
                    </p>
